<title>Reading Rhythm 8: Dotted Notes</title>
<metadata xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml">
  <md:content-id>m63120</md:content-id>
  <md:title>Reading Rhythm 8: Dotted Notes</md:title>
  <md:abstract>In common notation, a dot immediately to the right of a note makes the note longer, adding an extra half of the note's original length.</md:abstract>
  <md:uuid>a9a5c652-b6dc-4494-a7be-571fde55a846</md:uuid>
</metadata>

<content>
  <note id="eip-768">This lesson is part of <link document="col12057">Reading Rhythm</link>, a <link document="m62540">learning by doing</link> course intended to help you learn and practice the rhythm aspect of common notation. The pitch aspect of common notation is not covered in this course, so it can be used with any instrument, including voice, or with no instrument at all (using, for example, hand claps instead). This is a short experimental course that will be refined and expanded if there is sufficient user interest and feedback.</note><para id="eip-854">Lessons 5 through 7 introduced a variety of ways to write complex rhythms. There is one more common way to write complex rhythms: <term>dotted notes</term> or <term>dotted rhythms</term>. A dot immediately to the right of a note means “<emphasis>add another half of the original length of the note</emphasis>”. For example, a dotted half note will be the length of a half-plus-a-quarter-note. A dotted quarter is the same length as a quarter-plus-an-eighth-note . You may be wondering “why not simply write a half note tied to a quarter note”? That is always an option, but the dotted note is easier to write, and once you become accustomed to it, also easier to read (see <link target-id="dotted-figure"/>). “Dotted rhythms” are very common in most styles of music, so you will likely get plenty of practice reading them. Like tied notes, they can be a little difficult to play correctly at first, because they usually involve starting the note after the dot on a weaker beat, or a weaker part of the beat.</para><figure id="dotted-figure"><title>Dotted Notes</title><media id="dotted" alt="Shows dotted whole equivalent to tied whole plus half note; dotted as equivalent to tied half plus quarter note; dotted quarter equivalent to tied quarter plus eighth note; and dotted eighth equivalent to eighth plus sixteenth note.">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/dotted.png"/>
  </media>
<caption>A dotted note sounds as long as the original note (i.e. without the dot) plus half of the length of the original note. Any dotted rhythm can also be written as two notes tied together, with the second note half the length of the first.
  </caption>
</figure>

<para id="eip-445">Dotted rests are allowed, but are not as common as dotted notes; writing the separate rests (for example, a quarter rest followed by an eighth rest) is generally considered easier to read.</para><para id="eip-979">The suggested Activities in <link document="m62711">Lesson 5</link> involved only long tied notes (such as half and whole notes). Fast, complex rhythms involving shorter notes can be quite tricky to play accurately, and there are any number of complex rhythms that can be written using tied notes. There are a more limited number of possibilities with dotted notes, so it is worth practicing the most common ones, beginning with the slowest and easiest. </para><list id="eip-677" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic"><title>Activity 1: Read dotted half notes</title><item>Using any favorite <link document="m62591" target-id="eip-405">method of keeping a steady beat</link> and favorite <link document="m62591" target-id="eip-494">method of practicing rhythms</link>, try to read and play the examples in <link target-id="activity8-1-figure"/>.</item>
<item>Practice each example more than once, then listen to the sound files to check whether you have played them correctly.</item>
<item>If needed, try playing along with the sound file.</item></list><figure id="activity8-1-figure"><title>Practice Exercises: Dotted Half Notes</title><media id="activity8-1" alt="Two lines of mixed whole, half, quarter, eighth, and sixteenth notes and rests, with some of the half notes dotted.">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/activity8-1.png"/>
  </media>
</figure>

<figure id="rhythm8-1A-audio"><media id="rhythm8-1A" alt="Played on cymbals"> <audio mime-type="audio/mp3" src="rhythm8-1A.mp3"/> </media>  <caption>Activity 1 Line A (with only 3 preparation beats) (Audio examples in the text are provided <link document="m62590" target-id="eip-48">as mp3 files</link>. If you prefer wav files, those are provided <link target-id="rhythm8-1A-audio-w">below</link>.)</caption></figure><figure id="rhythm8-1B2-audio"> <media id="rhythm8-1B2" alt="Played on cymbals"> <audio mime-type="audio/mp3" src="rhythm8-1B2.mp3"/> </media> <caption>Activity 1 Line B with half-note beat</caption> </figure> 

