<list id="eip-324" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic"><title>Activity 2: Read dotted quarter notes</title><item>Using any favorite method of keeping the beat and practicing rhythms, try to read and play the examples in <link target-id="activity8-2-figure"/>.</item>
<item>Practice each example more than once, then listen to the sound files to check whether you have played them correctly. Remember that 6/8 is a <link document="m63106" target-id="eip-840">compound meter</link>. Three eighth notes (or one dotted quarter note!) will equal one beat, so in this meter, dotted quarters are relatively easy to play correctly.</item>
<item>If needed, try playing along with the sound file.</item></list><figure id="activity8-2-figure"><title>Practice Exercises: Dotted Quarter Notes</title><media id="activity8-2" alt="Two lines of mixed whole, half, quarter, eighth, and sixteenth notes and rests, with some of the quarter notes dotted.">
