<list id="eip-881" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic"><title>Activity 4: Write dotted rhythms </title><item>Use your preferred <link document="m62677" target-id="eip-782">methods of writing down music</link>, setting up a steady beat, and playing what you have written.</item>
<item>Try writing down your own lines that include dotted notes. Dotted notes can be create complex, difficult-to-play rhythms, so keep your first attempts reasonably simple. Feel free to favor the dotted rhythms that you like or find easy to play, and leave out any that are not yet comfortable. If needed, use the exercises that you found relatively easy to play as templates, making only small alterations to create a new line.</item>
<item>Try playing what you have written. Feel free to make changes as needed to create rhythms that you like and can play</item>
<item>As you did with the <link document="m62677" target-id="eip-782">writing activity in Lesson 2</link>, practice and check until you are certain that you are playing your written rhythms correctly.</item></list><para id="eip-875">Sometimes a rhythm that sounds like a dotted rhythm will be written with the appropriate rest instead of a dot. As always, the point of using a rest is to have silence rather than a note during that time in the rhythm. You may also encounter eighth rests and sixteenth rests in other complex rhythms.</para><figure id="eighth-rest-figure"><title>Eighth Rests and Sixteenth Rests</title><media id="eighth-rest" alt="Images of eighth rest and sixteenth rest, with two staves showing similar rhythms written using dotted notes on one staff and notes with rests (instead of dots) in between them on the other.">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/eighth-rest.png"/>
  </media>
  
<caption>A rhythm that sounds very similar to a dotted rhythm may be written with the appropriate rest instead of with tied or dotted notes. Note that the only difference between the rhythms of the two lines is that there will be short silences in the second line that last as long as the dots last in the first line.
  </caption></figure>

<para id="eip-71">Occasionally a rhythm will be written with two dots following the same note. (More dots are allowed theoretically, but I have never seen more than two following the same note.) The second dot adds half the length of the first dot. For example, a half note followed by two dots would be the length of a half-plus-a-quarter-plus-an-eighth-note. <term>Double dotted</term> notes create unusual rhythms that are difficult to play accurately, so there are no activities for practicing them in this course. </para><figure id="double-dotted-figure"><title>Double-dotted Rhythms</title><media id="double-dotted" alt="On a staff, double-dotted half shown as equivalent to half plus quarter plus eighth notes, tied together; and double-dotted quarter shown as equivalent to quarter plus eighth plus sixteenth notes.">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/double-dotted.png"/>
  </media>
  
<caption>The second dot adds half of the length added by the first dot. Technically, more dots could be added following the same pattern, but such rhythms are very rare and difficult to perform accurately.
  </caption></figure>

<para id="eip-542">This course has been a short introduction to the basics of reading rhythms. Obviously, there are many possible rhythms that you have not yet practiced in any of the suggested activities. There is no way to cover all of the possibilities; the tremendous variety of possible rhythms are one of the things that keeps music interesting. However, <emphasis>you have seen the rules that govern nearly all rhythms written in common notation</emphasis>. As you read and practice more pieces, you will also become better at quickly reading and learning rhythms that you have not seen before. Whenever you are confronted with a tricky new rhythm, there are several things you can do to figure it out: </para><list id="eip-579"><item>Slow the music down and play it with beats that happen more often, using steps similar to those in <link document="m63105" target-id="eip-761">Activity 4 of Lesson 6</link>.</item>
<item>Listen to a recording of the piece. Note that <emphasis>this only works when you are certain that the recording and your written music agree on the rhythm</emphasis>. This will usually be the case for some genres (such as classical music), but other genres (such as pop music) have a tendency to simplify the written music. In these genres, you cannot count on the written rhythm being the same as the rhythm performed in a recording.</item>
<item>Ask for help from a music teacher or musician who is well trained in reading common notation.</item></list><list id="eip-466"><title>Suggestions for practice with "real music":</title><item>When you listen to favorite pieces of music, listen for rhythms that are similar to the dotted rhythms you practiced in the activities above.</item>
<item>If you have any written music for your instrument that includes dotted notes, practice reading that music.</item>
<item>If you are singing in a choir with a conductor and with written music, start noticing any dotted notes in the music.</item>
<item>Look for rhythms in your written music that are not the same as the ones you have already practiced in these lessons, but that have similar elements (different variations of ties, dots, unfamiliar time signatures, and so on). For each “new” rhythm you find, use the suggestions above to try to determine how to play it. Use the steps you have learned in this course to check carefully that you are playing it correctly. Then practice the rhythm until it is familiar and look for other instances of that same rhythm in your music.</item></list>

